<div align="left">
				<table border="0" width="590" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" id="table3">
					<tr>
						<td>
						<p class="subtitle">
				Greene &amp; Greene – A Style Suited to Handtools <span style="font-weight: 400">
				<font size="2">by David Trusty, UK</font></span></p>
						</td>
						<td align="center" width="8" height="26">
						&nbsp;</td>
						<td align="right" width="103" height="26">
						<a href="../../index.asp">
						<img border="0" src="../../../0_images/nav-utility/arrowBack.jpg" width="24" height="23"></a>&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: 700">1 of 
						4</span>&nbsp;<a href="g&green2.asp"><img border="0" src="../../../0_images/nav-utility/arrowNext.jpg" width="24" height="23"></a></td>
					</tr>
				</table>
				<div align="left">
					<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" id="table5">
						<tr>
							<td align="left" valign="top" height="20">
							&nbsp;</td>
							<td width="10" height="20">&nbsp;</td>
							<td width="363" align="center" valign="top" height="20">
							&nbsp;</td>
						</tr>
						<tr>
							<td align="left" valign="top">
							<img border="1" src="0_img/dTrusty2.jpg" width="210" height="246"><span style="font-weight: 700"><p align="center"><A HREF="javascript:popUp('dTrusty.asp')">David Trusty</a></p>

							<td width="10">&nbsp;</td>
							<td width="363" align="center" valign="top">
							<p style="text-indent: 30px" align="left">
							&nbsp;</p>
							<p style="text-indent: 30px" align="left">
							I needed a desk and to learn handtool skills.&nbsp; 
							What would provide the best style for these dual 
							purposes?&nbsp; A Greene &amp; Greene desk.</p>
							<p align="left">
							<b>Why Greene &amp; Greene?</b></p>
							<p style="text-indent: 30px" align="left">
							<span lang="EN-GB">Of the several Arts &amp; Crafts 
							traditions that have evolved over the last hundred 
							and so years, Greene &amp; Greene is perhaps the most 
							elegant and coherent.&nbsp; It’s a matter of taste 
							but…..&nbsp; Mission always seems a little too 
							rectilinear; the English tradition overburdened by a 
							mock-medieval heaviness; the developments of 
							Mackintosh and Lloyd-Wright unsuited to human 
							comfort.</span></p></td>
						</tr>
					</table>
				</div>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Look at any Greene &amp; Greene design 
				and you see grace, tactility and organic solidity.&nbsp; Those 
				curves are easy on the eye and just as easy on your body, as you 
				sit in the chair, at the desk or table.&nbsp; Nothing jabs the 
				sensitive parts and the hand melds naturally with the curve of 
				arm rest or drawer pull.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">And then there’s the warm glow of 
				mahogany, reminiscent of a well-lived in home where people have 
				settled into a quiet harmony with those cherished objects, 
				including the furniture, that trace out their history.&nbsp; 
				Greene &amp; Greene belongs in such homes, where the interior 
				eschews passing fashions or fads in favor of things having 
				longevity in both their utility and their beauty.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Greene &amp; Greene seemed the obvious 
				style for one already enamored of the “honest” design and 
				joinery traditions of Arts &amp; Crafts.&nbsp; It would be a 
				challenge, with its heavy round-overs, carved pulls, cloud lift 
				brackets and so forth; but suitable for my modest learning 
				ambitions.&nbsp; And it would blend, to some degree, with a home 
				already filled with Shaker, Mission and other Arts &amp; Crafts 
				styles.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">I needed a new desk for the 
				ever-growing computer stuff - a large, flat surface for screens, 
				scanner, photo printer and so forth, as well as drawers for the 
				many disks, photo paper, memory keys, connecting cables and the 
				like.&nbsp; An old drop-front desk was meeting the need, after a 
				fashion, but was overflowing untidily with computer “stuff”, 
				much to the annoyance of the ladywife.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">So, it would be a G &amp; G desk with a 
				design dictated by its intended usage and location.&nbsp; It 
				would be 180 centimeters by 65 centimeters to fit the computing 
				alcove; and of a height to allow some shallow drawers; but also 
				allow me to sit with knees tucked under, at the right height to 
				operate the keyboard et al.&nbsp; Within these dimensions, 
				however, all must manifest G &amp; G motifs and proportions.&nbsp; 
				The several planks of Afrormosia recovered from old chemistry 
				benches thrown out by the local university provided a timber 
				most suitable for such a G &amp; G piece.</p>
				<p align="center"><img border="1" src="0_img/image001.jpg"></p>
				<p><b>Taking up Hand Tools</b></p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Well, the foregoing explains part 
				of the appeal that a G &amp; G desk has for me.&nbsp; But it offered 
				another advantage - a style that this keen-to-learn woodworker 
				might find challenging in which to build a first piece entirely 
				with hand tools.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">I really didn’t want to wade into 
				that precious Afrormosia without first knowing what tools to 
				employ and how to use them.&nbsp; The first decision was: buy 
				the best (within my means).</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Now, some folk will always persuade 
				themselves that either “value = cheap” or that they do not 
				deserve something that costs above some imagined norm or 
				arbitrarily-chosen budgetary limit.&nbsp; A former life as a 
				racing cyclist had taught me the folly of skimping on equipment.&nbsp; 
				Why ride gas tubes and other heavy, bendy metal when there are 
				carbon fiber frames and titanium accoutrements to dangle 
				thereupon?&nbsp; These costly items do work better, weigh less 
				(important in hilly races) and… give a psychological boost.&nbsp; 
				Indeed, you feel your efforts must live up to the expenditure.&nbsp; 
				So it is with any tool.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">So some of my saws are from Mike 
				Wenzloff, my planes from Philip Marcou and my chisels from Dave 
				Jeske (Blue Spruce).&nbsp; There are also cheaper but very 
				functional items from mass-production sources, in my collection: 
				VERITAS; Lie Nielsen; Two Cherries; Zona; and so forth.&nbsp; 
				But there are no Records, Anants and similar.&nbsp; Why saw, 
				plane and chisel with gas pipe, as it were, if the pension can 
				stand the purchase of better-wrought tools?</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Nor are there any of the better, 
				renovated tools from olden times in my arsenal.&nbsp; It is hard 
				enough to learn hand tool use without also having to learn 
				bidding or buying conventions, as well as renovation skills.</p>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Of course having tools, of whatever 
				quality, does not automatically mean you can use them. The next 
				stage was to practice, practice, practice.</p>
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" id="table7">
					<tr>
						<td width="264" bordercolor="#000000" align="center" valign="top">
						<div align="center">
							<table border="1" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="6" id="table8" bordercolordark="#000000" bgcolor="#FFFF99" bordercolor="#000000">
								<tr>
									<td>
									<p align="center" style="margin-bottom:6.0pt;text-align:center">
									<b style="mso-bidi-font-weight: normal; font-style: italic">
									Expensive Tools<o:p></o:p></b></p>
									<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: 30px; margin-bottom: 6.0pt">
									<span style="font-size: 8pt">Does use of 
									those top-of-the-market tools make a 
									difference?&nbsp; Trying hard to put aside 
									the more emotional aspects of my judgment, I 
									contend that they do.</span></p>
									<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: 30px; margin-bottom: 6.0pt">
									<span style="font-size: 8pt">Afrormosia and 
									teak are hard, ornery timbers with difficult 
									grain.&nbsp; A Marcou S15A smoother with a 
									high angled blade set for a fine cut, along 
									with a closed mouth, will take off thin, 
									crispy shavings, even against the grain, 
									with no significant tear out.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>The planked top of the G &amp; G desk has 
									grain running in many contrary directions 
									yet required no scraping after the smoothing<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>plane, only a light hand-sand.</span></p>
									<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: 30px; margin-bottom: 6.0pt">
									<span style="font-size: 8pt">A small 
									<a target="_blank" href="http://www.leevalley.com/">VERITAS 
									BU</a> smoothing plane, with similar blade angle 
									and setting, will not perform so well 
									because it lacks weight and the associated 
									momentum, compared to the Marcou.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>With the necessary fine setting of 
									the blade, the lighter VERITAS will be more 
									inclined to slide and skip, especially on 
									oily woods. </span></p>
									<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: 30px; margin-bottom: 6.0pt">
									<span style="font-size: 8pt">
									<a target="_blank" href="http://www.wenzloffandsons.com/saws/index.html">Wenzloff saws</a> 
									are sharpened and set to a very high 
									standard (certainly compared to the
			<st1:City w:st="on">
			<st1:place w:st="on">Stanley</st1:place></st1:City> tenon saw and 
									Bahco panel saw that I have).<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>The blades are thin but stiff, flat 
									and at the ideal angle to the handle, which 
									seems made for your hand alone.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>These saws are well-set and cut true, 
									with no drift or other deviations from the 
									intended cutting line.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>They leave a surface that requires a 
									minimum of shoulder plane or chisel work to 
									size or smooth.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>In short, they cut where you want 
									them to and do so rapidly, time after time.</span></p>
									<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: 30px; margin-bottom: 6.0pt">
									<span style="font-size: 8pt">
									<a href="../../../ad/blueSpruce/check-blueSpruce-Articles.asp">Blue Spruce 
									chisels</a> are a joy to look at and handle – 
									their finish is superb.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>More to the point, the super-slim 
									aris and fine A2 blade allow the most 
									delicate of joints to be pared to a very 
									fine fit, with ease.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>
									<a target="_blank" href="../../../ad/traditionalwoodworker.com/check-traditionalwoodworker.com.asp">Two Cherries chisels</a> also hold a fine 
									edge and are comfortable; but they have 
									thick edges that mean they cannot get into 
									the corners of those fine joints.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>Blue Spruce might cost twice what the 
									Cherries cost but they are much more capable 
									of fine paring work and, unlike the 
									Cherries, come without the need to take off 
									a spurious and ugly coat of varnish from 
									both blades and handles.<span style="mso-spacerun:yes">&nbsp;
									</span>The Spruce’s carnauba wax 
									handle-finish is beautiful.<o:p></o:p></span></td>
								</tr>
							</table>
						</div>
						</td>
						<td width="10"></td>
						<td align="left" valign="top" width="313">
						<p style="text-indent: 30px">Like many other 
						woodworkers, I have a peculiar aversion to practicing 
						without at the same time making something.&nbsp; 
						Nevertheless, I did produce a few dozen dovetails, 
						mortise &amp; tenons and finger joints in scrap before 
						turning to jointing the doors and drawers for the 
						newly-made workbench, as well as a few little boxes.&nbsp;&nbsp; 
						I also planed away to nothing (purely to understand the 
						action of the planes at various settings) many nasty 
						bits of hardwood that I had been too mean to throw out 
						but which were practically of no use in any foreseeable 
						piece of furniture I might make.</p>
						<p style="text-indent: 30px">All this practice was 
						certainly revealing.&nbsp; Whilst use of machine tools 
						requires one kind of skill, hand tools certainly require 
						another.&nbsp; They are very physical, requiring a lot 
						more muscle as well as muscle control.&nbsp; It is a lot 
						easier to make errors and also to injure yourself.&nbsp; 
						The dangerous parts of machines are obvious and easily 
						avoided; but handtools require your intimate, physical 
						involvement as you are their power source.&nbsp; Skinned 
						knuckles, nicks and bruises are unavoidable as you learn 
						the characteristic working strokes with hand tools.</p>
						<p><b>Designing the Desk</b></p>
						<p style="text-indent: 30px">Eventually I was ready 
						enough to attempt the G &amp; G.&nbsp; My usual “design” 
						method involves only some scale plans on graph paper – 
						no full scale plans or mock-ups for this lazy boy.&nbsp; 
						Nor do I like to use the ready-made plans of others, 
						especially when the dimensions of the piece are dictated 
						by its future use and location.</p>
						<p style="text-indent: 30px">At the time I had 3 sources 
						for G &amp; G design wisdom: the G &amp; G-related articles that 
						have appeared in Fine Woodworking; the photographic 
						essay of Bruce Smith &amp; Alexander Vertikoff and Daryl 
						Peart’s book.&nbsp; Although the latter majors in 
						machine-tool-oriented methods, the detail of cloud 
						lifts, bread board ends, plugs, brackets and other G &amp; G 
						motifs came mostly from there.&nbsp; </td>
					</tr>
				</table>
				<p style="text-indent: 30px">Since building the desk I have also 
				acquired Robert Lang’s excellent shop drawings of G &amp; G as well 
				as the even more stunning photographic essay of things G &amp; G by 
				Marvin Rand.&nbsp; These new acquisitions will be extremely 
				useful in helping with the next G &amp; G piece I make, which will 
				hopefully have a few more G &amp; G design refinements and details.</p>
